---
import BaseLayout from "../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro";
import { amortizationSchedule } from "../../lib/calc/loan";

const title = "If I Pay a $5,000 Lump Sum on My Mortgage (what changes?)";
const description =
  "See how a $5,000 principal-only lump sum can affect payoff time and interest, and why paying earlier usually saves more. Compare with monthly extras.";

const examplePrincipal = 300000;
const exampleApr = 6.5;
const exampleTermMonths = 360;
const exampleLumpSum = 5000;
const base = amortizationSchedule({ principal: examplePrincipal, aprPercent: exampleApr, termMonths: exampleTermMonths });
const withLumpEarly = amortizationSchedule({
  principal: examplePrincipal,
  aprPercent: exampleApr,
  termMonths: exampleTermMonths,
  extraOneTime: exampleLumpSum,
  extraOneTimeMonth: 1
});
const withLumpLate = amortizationSchedule({
  principal: examplePrincipal,
  aprPercent: exampleApr,
  termMonths: exampleTermMonths,
  extraOneTime: exampleLumpSum,
  extraOneTimeMonth: 24
});
const money0 = new Intl.NumberFormat("en-US", { style: "currency", currency: "USD", minimumFractionDigits: 0, maximumFractionDigits: 0 });
const pct2 = new Intl.NumberFormat("en-US", { minimumFractionDigits: 2, maximumFractionDigits: 2 });
const yearsMonths = (months: number) => ({ years: Math.floor(months / 12), months: months % 12 });
const baseYm = yearsMonths(base.months);
const earlyYm = yearsMonths(withLumpEarly.months);
const lateYm = yearsMonths(withLumpLate.months);
---
<BaseLayout title={title} description={description} canonicalPath="/guides/mortgage-lump-sum-5000" robots="noindex, follow">
  <section class="card hero">
    <span class="pill">Guide</span>
    <nav class="breadcrumbs" aria-label="Breadcrumb">
      <a href="/">Home</a>
      <span aria-hidden="true">/</span>
      <a href="/guides">Guides</a>
      <span aria-hidden="true">/</span>
      <span aria-current="page">$5,000 lump sum</span>
    </nav>
    <h1>If I pay a $5,000 lump sum on my mortgage, what happens?</h1>
    <p>
      A lump sum that is applied as principal-only reduces your balance immediately. That usually lowers future interest and can shorten
      payoff time. Timing matters: a lump sum early often saves more than the same lump sum later.
    </p>
    <div class="btn-row">
      <a class="btn" href="/topics/mortgage-payoff">Mortgage payoff topic hub</a>
      <a class="btn btn-primary" href="/calculators/additional-principal-payment-calculator">Model a lump sum</a>
      <a class="btn" href="/guides/principal-only-extra-payments">Principal-only checklist</a>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="card section prose" style="margin-top:18px">
    <h2 style="margin-top:0">How to model the timing</h2>
    <ol class="muted" style="margin:10px 0 0; padding-left:18px">
      <li>Enter your principal, rate, and term in the calculator.</li>
      <li>Set one-time extra to $5,000.</li>
      <li>Change the one-time month (early vs later) and compare results.</li>
      <li>Compare the lump sum to a monthly extra amount that fits your budget.</li>
    </ol>
  </section>

  <section class="card section prose" style="margin-top:18px">
    <h2 style="margin-top:0">Why timing matters</h2>
    <p class="muted" style="margin:10px 0 0">
      Interest is calculated on the remaining balance. A lump sum today reduces that balance immediately, which lowers interest every
      month after it. The same lump sum later still helps, but it affects fewer months of interest.
    </p>
    <p class="muted" style="margin:12px 0 0">
      If you are deciding between "save more first" and "pay a smaller amount now," model both. Often the earlier payment wins unless the
      later lump sum is much larger.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section class="grid" style="margin-top:18px">
    <div class="card section prose col-6">
      <h2 style="margin-top:0">Lump sum vs monthly extra</h2>
      <p class="muted" style="margin:10px 0 0">
        If you can only pay extra occasionally, a lump sum can still help. If you can pay extra monthly, earlier recurring principal
        reduction can outperform a lump sum that happens much later.
      </p>
    </div>
    <div class="card section prose col-6">
      <h2 style="margin-top:0">What to confirm</h2>
      <ul class="muted" style="margin:10px 0 0; padding-left:18px">
        <li>Lump sum is applied as principal-only (not "paid ahead").</li>
        <li>No prepayment penalty applies.</li>
        <li>Your servicer posts the payment when you expect.</li>
      </ul>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="card section prose" style="margin-top:18px">
    <h2 style="margin-top:0">If $5,000 is your budget</h2>
    <p class="muted" style="margin:10px 0 0">
      If $5,000 is what you can afford comfortably, it's often better to apply it now than to wait for a larger amount that might not come
      for a year or two. The trade-off is liquidity, so keep enough cash for emergencies.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section class="card section prose" style="margin-top:18px">
    <h2 style="margin-top:0">Compare to other options</h2>
    <p class="muted" style="margin:10px 0 0">
      If you want a bigger impact, compare the $5,000 lump sum to either a monthly extra (for example $150 to $250) or a larger lump sum
      like $10,000. The calculator can show which option shortens payoff more over your expected time horizon.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section class="card section prose" style="margin-top:18px">
    <h2 style="margin-top:0">Pay down or invest?</h2>
    <p class="muted" style="margin:10px 0 0">
      A lump sum provides a guaranteed return equal to your mortgage rate saved. Investing may offer higher returns but carries risk and
      less certainty. If you need liquidity, consider a smaller lump sum plus a monthly extra instead of using all $5,000 at once.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section class="card section prose" style="margin-top:18px">
    <h2 style="margin-top:0">Split strategy (lump sum + monthly)</h2>
    <p class="muted" style="margin:10px 0 0">
      A common approach is to pay a smaller lump sum now and add a modest monthly extra afterward. This captures early interest savings
      while keeping enough cash on hand for emergencies. The calculator can help you test a split strategy like $2,500 now plus $100/month.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section class="card section prose" style="margin-top:18px">
    <h2 style="margin-top:0">Worked example (computed)</h2>
    <p class="muted" style="margin:10px 0 0">
      Example: {money0.format(examplePrincipal)} at {pct2.format(exampleApr)}% APR for {exampleTermMonths} months. Compare baseline to a
      one-time {money0.format(exampleLumpSum)} principal-only lump sum in month 1, then compare to the same lump sum applied later.
    </p>
    <div style="overflow:auto; margin-top:12px">
      <table class="table">
        <thead>
          <tr>
            <th>Scenario</th>
            <th class="num">Lump sum</th>
            <th class="num">Payoff time</th>
            <th class="num">Total interest</th>
          </tr>
        </thead>
        <tbody>
          <tr>
            <td>Baseline</td>
            <td class="num">{money0.format(0)}</td>
            <td class="num">{base.months} months ({baseYm.years}y {baseYm.months}m)</td>
            <td class="num">{money0.format(base.totalInterest)}</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td>Lump sum in month 1</td>
            <td class="num">{money0.format(exampleLumpSum)}</td>
            <td class="num">{withLumpEarly.months} months ({earlyYm.years}y {earlyYm.months}m)</td>
            <td class="num">{money0.format(withLumpEarly.totalInterest)}</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td>Lump sum in month 24</td>
            <td class="num">{money0.format(exampleLumpSum)}</td>
            <td class="num">{withLumpLate.months} months ({lateYm.years}y {lateYm.months}m)</td>
            <td class="num">{money0.format(withLumpLate.totalInterest)}</td>
          </tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>
    </div>
    <p class="muted" style="margin:12px 0 0">
      In this example, the month 1 lump sum saves about{" "}
      {money0.format(Math.max(0, base.totalInterest - withLumpEarly.totalInterest))} in interest and shortens payoff by{" "}
      {Math.max(0, base.months - withLumpEarly.months)} months (calculator estimate).
    </p>
  </section>

  <section class="card section prose" style="margin-top:18px">
    <h2 style="margin-top:0">Time horizon check</h2>
    <p class="muted" style="margin:10px 0 0">
      If you plan to sell or refinance within a few years, compare savings over that shorter window. A late lump sum can deliver much
      less benefit before you exit the loan, even if it looks meaningful over the full term.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section class="card section prose" style="margin-top:18px">
    <h2 style="margin-top:0">Checklist: timing and cash flow</h2>
    <ul class="muted" style="margin:10px 0 0; padding-left:18px">
      <li><strong>Earlier is better:</strong> a lump sum early typically saves more interest.</li>
      <li><strong>Principal-only:</strong> confirm the payment is applied directly to principal.</li>
      <li><strong>Emergency fund:</strong> keep enough liquidity for unexpected expenses.</li>
      <li><strong>Compare alternatives:</strong> a small monthly extra can beat a late lump sum.</li>
    </ul>
  </section>

  <section class="card section prose" style="margin-top:18px">
    <h2 style="margin-top:0">Statement check</h2>
    <ul class="muted" style="margin:10px 0 0; padding-left:18px">
      <li>Confirm the lump sum posts as principal-only, not "paid ahead."</li>
      <li>Match the payment posting date when modeling timing.</li>
      <li>If the servicer applies extra payments after the due date, model a later month.</li>
    </ul>
  </section>

  <section class="card section prose" style="margin-top:18px">
    <h2 style="margin-top:0">FAQ</h2>
    <h3 style="margin:12px 0 0">Is $5,000 enough to matter?</h3>
    <p class="muted" style="margin:8px 0 0">
      It can, especially early in the loan. The impact depends on your rate and remaining term.
    </p>
    <h3 style="margin:12px 0 0">Should I wait and save a bigger lump sum?</h3>
    <p class="muted" style="margin:8px 0 0">
      Waiting can reduce interest savings. If the money is available now, compare a smaller lump sum today to a larger one later.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section class="card section prose" style="margin-top:18px">
    <h2 style="margin-top:0">References</h2>
    <ul class="muted" style="margin:10px 0 0; padding-left:18px">
      <li>
        CFPB:{" "}
        <a href="https://www.consumerfinance.gov/consumer-tools/mortgages/" rel="noopener noreferrer" target="_blank">
          Mortgages resources
        </a>
      </li>
    </ul>
  </section>

  <section class="card section prose" style="margin-top:18px">
    <h2 style="margin-top:0">Next steps</h2>
    <div class="btn-row" style="margin-top:10px">
      <a class="btn btn-primary" href="/calculators/extra-payment-calculator">Compare to monthly extra</a>
      <a class="btn" href="/guides/mortgage-lump-sum-10000">Pay a $10,000 lump sum</a>
      <a class="btn" href="/guides/amortization-with-extra-payments">Amortization with extra payments</a>
    </div>
    <p class="muted" style="margin:12px 0 0">Educational use only. Not financial advice.</p>
    <p class="muted" style="margin:12px 0 0; font-size:13px">Last updated: 2026-01-29</p>
  </section>
</BaseLayout>
